{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609617"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:48:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:48:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16108"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16108"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.1,0.14,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8799"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115198"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8799"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16108"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97206"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8678"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21006"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115198"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, the primitive gonads begin to form from intermediate mesoderm in week 5.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical location where primitive gonadal development first occurs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gonadal ridge on posterior abdominal wall","Lateral plate mesoderm","Urogenital sinus","Genital tubercle","Coelomic cavity"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egonadal ridge on the posterior abdominal wall\u003C/strong\u003E is the site where primitive gonadal development begins. This ridge forms from intermediate mesoderm and is initially identical in both male and female embryos. The gonadal ridge develops medial to the mesonephros (primitive kidney) and contains primordial germ cells that migrate from the yolk sac.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral plate mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the body wall and limbs but is not the site of gonadal development. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eurogenital sinus\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to parts of the bladder and urethra but not the gonads. The \u003Cstrong\u003Egenital tubercle\u003C/strong\u003E develops into external genitalia but is not involved in gonadal formation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoelomic cavity\u003C/strong\u003E is the body cavity that contains the developing organs but is not the site of gonadal development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gonadal ridge will later differentiate into either testes or ovaries depending on genetic sex and the presence or absence of SRY gene expression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The gonadal ridge forms from intermediate mesoderm on the posterior abdominal wall during week 5 of embryonic development.","The gonadal ridge gives rise to both male and female gonads before sex-specific differentiation occurs.","The gonadal ridge develops adjacent to the mesonephros, which provides important developmental signals."],"references":["Lucas-Herald AK, Bashamboo A. Gonadal development. Endocr Dev. 2014;27:1-16. doi: 10.1159/000363608. Epub 2014 Sep 11. PMID: 25247640.","Lorenzi V, Vento-Tormo R, Garcia-Alonso L. Human gonadal development, cell by cell. Clin Transl Med. 2022 Dec;12(12):e1123. doi: 10.1002/ctm2.1123. PMID: 36513876; PMCID: PMC9747682","Xie Y, Wu C, Li Z, Wu Z, Hong L. Early Gonadal Development and Sex Determination in Mammal. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Jul 6;23(14):7500. doi: 10.3390/ijms23147500. PMID: 35886859; PMCID: PMC9323860","Gilbert SF. Developmental Biology. 6th edition. Sunderland (MA): Sinauer Associates; 2000. Intermediate Mesoderm. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10089/","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97206"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16108"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97206"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T09:49:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T09:52:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8799"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115198"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null